<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,909,1747]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,986,1012]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Description.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[419,521,986,1012]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">holotype</typeStatus>
is a colony fragment with part of the holdfast still present. It has a bushy colony shape and anastomoses, the latter mostly situated in the lower part of the colony. The colony is 
<quantity box="[1363,1436,1025,1051]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="cm" value="22.0">22 cm</quantity>
high and about 
<quantity box="[336,410,1064,1090]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="cm" value="12.0">12 cm</quantity>
wide, the main stem is 
<quantity box="[695,776,1064,1090]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="cm" value="0.5">0.5 cm</quantity>
wide and branching starts at 
<quantity box="[1128,1209,1064,1090]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="cm" value="0.5">0.5 cm</quantity>
above the holdfast (
<figureCitation box="[159,245,1102,1128]" captionStart="FIGURE 7. a" captionStartId="13.[151,255,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[175,1418,197,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[175,1419,197,1953]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. a, RMNH Coel. 38768, holotype of Astrogorgia fruticosa n. sp.; b, RMNH Coel. 38769, Echinogorgia sp. a; c, RMNH Coel. 38770, Echinogorgia sp. b; d, RMNH Coel. 38771, Echinogorgia sp. b. Scales 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186750/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,230,1102,1128]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="7.0">7</number>
a
</figureCitation>
). Polyps are situated all around the branches; calyces are about 
<quantity box="[992,1060,1102,1128]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
high.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,909,1747]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Polyps are retracted; the collaret has 
<number box="[656,701,1141,1167]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7</number>
rows of spindles and the points have many sclerites. These sclerites do not differ much from those of the calyx, and are up to 
<quantity box="[958,1067,1180,1206]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="0.25">0.25 mm</quantity>
long, with simple tubercles or spines (
<figureCitation box="[239,309,1218,1244]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,259,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[175,1418,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[175,1419,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Astrogorgia fruticosa n. sp., holotype RMNH Coel. 38768: a, polyp spindles; b, tentacular rods; c-d, coenenchymal spindles; e, capstans and rods of the subsurface layer. Scale at d only applies to d." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186751/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[294,309,1218,1244]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
a). Tentacle sclerites are similar to those of the points but slightly shorter, more flattened and less tuberculate (
<figureCitation box="[297,367,1257,1283]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,259,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[175,1418,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[175,1419,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Astrogorgia fruticosa n. sp., holotype RMNH Coel. 38768: a, polyp spindles; b, tentacular rods; c-d, coenenchymal spindles; e, capstans and rods of the subsurface layer. Scale at d only applies to d." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186751/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[352,367,1257,1283]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
b).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,909,1747]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
The surface layer of the coenenchyme has spindles up to 
<quantity box="[866,971,1296,1322]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.60 mm</quantity>
long; with simple or complex tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[159,228,1334,1360]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,259,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[175,1418,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[175,1419,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Astrogorgia fruticosa n. sp., holotype RMNH Coel. 38768: a, polyp spindles; b, tentacular rods; c-d, coenenchymal spindles; e, capstans and rods of the subsurface layer. Scale at d only applies to d." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186751/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,228,1334,1360]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
c–d). The interior of the coenenchyme has capstans and rods, up to 
<quantity box="[1011,1115,1334,1360]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.10 mm</quantity>
long, with simple tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[159,229,1373,1399]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="14.[151,259,1972,1996]" captionTargetBox="[175,1418,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[175,1419,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 8. Astrogorgia fruticosa n. sp., holotype RMNH Coel. 38768: a, polyp spindles; b, tentacular rods; c-d, coenenchymal spindles; e, capstans and rods of the subsurface layer. Scale at d only applies to d." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186751/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,229,1373,1399]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
e).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,909,1747]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,295,1411,1437]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Colour.</emphasis>
Colony red, tentacle sclerites yellow, point sclerites partly yellow partly reddish; all other sclerites are reddish.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1194,1488,1515]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,909,1747]" box="[197,1194,1488,1515]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,338,1488,1514]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Etymology.</emphasis>
The Latin 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[467,482,1488,1514]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">“</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[482,591,1489,1515]" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fruticosa">fruticosa</taxonomicName>
”, bushy or full of bushes, refers to the colony form.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,909,1747]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,321,1527,1553]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Remarks.</emphasis>
Only three other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[665,808,1528,1553]" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[665,808,1528,1553]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Astrogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been reported having a bushy colony form, 
<taxonomicName authority="Thompson &amp; Simpson, 1909" authorityName="Thompson &amp; Simpson" authorityYear="1909" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="arborea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. arborea</emphasis>
(Thompson &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Simpson" box="[426,603,1566,1592]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" refString="Thomson, J. A. &amp; Simpson J. J. (1909) An account of the alcyonarians collected by the Royal Indian Marine Survey Ship Investigator in the Indian Ocean; with a report on the species of Dendronephthya by W. D. Henderson. II. The alcyonarians of the littoral area. Calcutta, The Indian Museum, i - xviii + 1 - 319." type="book chapter" year="1909">
Simpson, 
<number box="[543,603,1566,1592]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="1909.0">1909</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[684,747,1566,1592]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Grasshoff, 1999" authorityName="Grasshoff" authorityYear="1999" box="[759,1099,1566,1592]" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="mengalia">
<emphasis box="[759,902,1567,1592]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. mengalia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Grasshoff" box="[909,1099,1566,1592]" pageId="11" pageNumber="50" refString="Grasshoff, M. (1999) The shallow water gorgonians of New Caledonia and adjacent islands (Coelenterata: Octocorallia). Senckenbergiana biologica 78 (1 / 2), 1 - 245." type="journal article" year="1999">
Grasshoff, 
<number box="[1040,1099,1566,1592]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1171,1353,1566,1592]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hermanlimianto &amp; Ofwegen, 2006" authorityName="Hermanlimianto &amp; Ofwegen" authorityYear="2006" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="balinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. balinensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hermanlimianto" box="[277,687,1605,1631]" pageId="11" pageNumber="51" refString="Hermanlimianto, M. I. Y. T. &amp; Ofwegen, L. P. van (2006) A new species of Astrogorgia (Coelenterata: Octocorallia: Plexauridae) from Bali. Zoologische Mededelingen Leiden 80 - 4 (10), 103 - 108." type="journal article" year="2006">
Hermanlimianto &amp; Ofwegen, 
<number box="[629,687,1605,1631]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Bali. 
<taxonomicName box="[823,949,1605,1630]" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="arborea">
<emphasis box="[823,949,1605,1630]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. arborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has spindles up to 
<quantity box="[1174,1264,1605,1631]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
long and in 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="mengalia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. mengalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are up to 
<quantity box="[434,524,1644,1670]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
long; both much longer than the 
<quantity box="[912,1017,1644,1670]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.60 mm</quantity>
of the present species. On the other hand 
<taxonomicName box="[216,370,1683,1708]" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="balinensis">
<emphasis box="[216,370,1683,1708]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. balinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has much shorter spindles, up to 
<quantity box="[771,877,1682,1708]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="0.25">0.25 mm</quantity>
long. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName box="[1084,1223,1683,1708]" class="Anthozoa" family="Plexauridae" genus="Astrogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fruticosa">
<emphasis box="[1084,1223,1683,1708]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. fruticosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has anastomoses, the other three bushy species do not.
</paragraph>
